					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-665415#post-1805986</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-665415/scp-1838#post-1805986</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Fri, 28 Jun 2013 18:34:31 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>Benjamin Stokes</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>826567</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>I like it! Two minor gripes.</p> <p>Gripe 1:</p> <p>&quot;It is unclear how this occurs, but the majority of hamburgers, hot dogs, fried chicken, or fried potatoes cooked or prepared by these individuals will possess the same properties as SCP-1838-2, and are thus capable of propagating the anomaly.&quot;</p> <p>In my view, the whole &quot;it is unclear how this occurs, but&quot; part is unnecessary. If you must point out that how this happens is not yet understood (something that would already be implied if you wrote nothing at all about the method), then maybe something like this would sound more professional:</p> <p>&quot;The majority of hamburgers, hot dogs, fried chicken, or fried potatoes cooked or prepared by these individuals will possess the same properties as SCP-1838-2, and are thus capable of propagating the anomaly. The mechanism by which this occurs is unknown.&quot;</p> <p>Gripe 2:</p> <p>Unless I'm missing something, the whole situation seems very, very difficult to control. <em>Any</em> sporting event? Up to <em>four</em> at one time? The effects can then <em>spread</em> from person to person? The Foundation may have a ridiculous amount of resources at their disposal, sure, but I still can't quite believe that there hasn't already been one or more massive and (dare I say it?) un-coverup-able breaches.</p> <p>I'm going to go ahead and upvote despite these two concerns, because it really is a good article overall.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
